<span class="displaytext"><b>arlington, va -- </b>today, (candidate last) spokesman tucker bounds issued the following statement concerning (candidate full)'s statement that those accusing him of changing positions "haven't apparently been listening to me": <p><i>"since becoming his party's presumptive nominee, (candidate full) has changed numerous positions and will continue to change his stances as he puts politics ahead of principle. from growing our economy to securing our nation, (candidate full) has proven his rhetoric to be nothing but empty words and broken pledges that are at odds with his left wing partisan record. (candidate full) is wrong: everyone's been listening and still nobody knows what (candidate full) truly believes."</i> </p><p><b>today, (candidate full) said that those accusing him of changing his position "haven't apparently been listening to me." </b>"asked by a voter about accusations of flip-flopping, (PARTY NAME) (candidate full) dismissed the notion tuesday that he has been shifting stances on iraq, guns and the death penalty to break with his party's liberal wing and court a wider swath of voters. 'the people who say this haven't apparently been listening to me,' the likely (PARTY NAME) presidential nominee said in response to a question at a town-hall style event." (liz sidoti, "(candidate last) denies shifting to reach political center," <i>the associated press</i>, 7/8/08)<br/> </p><p><b><u><br/>change #1: despite pledging to withdraw american troops from iraq immediately, (candidate full) now says he would "refine" his policy after listening to the commanders on the ground</u></b> </p><p><b>in july 2008, (candidate full) said he will continue to "refine" his iraq policy. </b>(candidate last): "i've always said that the pace of withdrawal would be dictated by the safety and security of our troops and the need to maintain stability. that assessment has not changed...and when i go to iraq and have a chance to talk to some of the commanders on the ground, i'm sure i'll have more information and will continue to refine my policies." (jeff zeleny, "(candidate last): open to 'refine' iraq withdrawal timeline," <i>the new york times'</i> "the caucus" blog, <a href="http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/07/03/(candidate last)-open-to-refine-iraq-withdrawal-timeline/">http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com</a>, 7/3/08)</p><p><b>in the primaries, (candidate full) committed to withdrawing troops from iraq regardless of the advice he received from commanders on the ground.</b> abc's charles gibson: "and, senator (candidate last), your campaign manager, david plouffe, said, 'when he is' -- this is talking about you - 'when he is elected president, we will be out of iraq in 16 months at the most. there should be no confusion about that.' so you'd give the same rock-hard pledge, that no matter what the military commanders said, you would give the order to bring them home?" (candidate last): "because the commander-in-chief sets the mission, charlie. that's not the role of the generals. ... now, i will always listen to our commanders on the ground with respect to tactics, once i've given them a new mission, that we are going to proceed deliberately, in an orderly fashion, out of iraq, and we are going to have our combat troops out. we will not have permanent bases there. once i have provided that mission, if they come to me and want to adjust tactics, then i will certainly take their recommendations into consideration. but, ultimately, the buck stops with me as the commander-in-chief." (sen. (candidate full), (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate, philadelphia, pa, 4/16/08) </p><p><b><u><br/>change #2: despite pledging to accept public financing, (candidate full) has reversed his position and opted out of the system</u></b> </p><p><b>(candidate full) has declined public financing in the general election, calling it a "broken system." </b>"in a web video emailed to supporters, (candidate last) asks his supporters to help him 'declare our independence from a broken system.' of course, it's not so much a broken system that explains why he's passing on the fec's $80+million. he will easily raise more than he could ever get in public funding." (jonathan martin, "(candidate last) opts out of public financing," <i>the politico</i>'s "jonathan martin" blog, <a href="http://www.politico.com/blogs/jonathanmartin/0608/(candidate last)_opts_out_of_public_financing_.html">www.politico.com</a>, 6/19/08) </p><p><b>in response to a midwest democracy network questionnaire, (candidate full) said he would accept public funding in the general election. </b>question: "if you are nominated for president in 2008 and your major opponents agree to forgo private funding in the general election campaign, will you participate in the presidential public financing system?" (candidate last): "yes. i have been a long-time advocate for public financing of campaigns combined with free television and radio time as a way to reduce the influence of moneyed special interests." (sen. (candidate full), "presidential candidate questionnaire," midwest democracy network, <a href="http://www.commoncause.org/atf/cf/%7bfb3c17e2-cdd1-4df6-92be-bd4429893665%7d/mdnnationalrelease.pdf">www.commoncause.org</a>, 11/27/07) </p><p><b><u><br/>change #3: (candidate full) is backtracking on his support for unilaterally renegotiating nafta</u></b> </p><p><b>during the primaries, (candidate full) pledged to unilaterally renegotiate nafta.</b> nbc's tim russert: "a simple question. will you as president say to canada and mexico, this [nafta] has not worked for us, we are out?" (candidate last): "i will make sure that we renegotiate in the same way that senator (candidate last) talked about, and i think actually senator (candidate last)'s answer on this one is right. i think we should use the hammer of a potential opt-out as leverage to ensure that we actually get labor and environmental standards that are enforced." (sen. (candidate full), msnbc (PARTY NAME) presidential debate, cleveland, oh, 2/26/08)</p><p><b>in the general election, (candidate full) now says his words were "overheated and amplified."</b> "in an interview with fortune to be featured in the magazine's upcoming issue, the presumptive (PARTY NAME) nominee backed off his harshest attacks on the free trade agreement and indicated he didn't want to unilaterally reopen negotiations on nafta. 'sometimes during campaigns the rhetoric gets overheated and amplified,' he conceded, after i reminded him that he had called nafta 'devastating' and 'a big mistake,' despite nonpartisan studies concluding that the trade zone has had a mild, positive effect on the u.s. economy." (nina easton, "(candidate last): nafta not so bad after all," <i>fortune</i>, 6/18/08) </p><p><b><u><br/>change #4: (candidate full) is considering reducing corporate taxes despite having called corporate tax cuts "the exact wrong prescription for america"</u></b> </p><p><b><i>the wall street journal</i></b><b> reported that (candidate full) would consider lowering corporate taxes. </b>"sen. (candidate last)'s nod to lowering corporate taxes comes as (PARTY NAME)s have been attacking him for proposals that would raise the cost of doing business, such as his pledge to raise the tax rate on capital gains, and his vow to increase the top income-tax rates, which are often used by small, unincorporated enterprises. he didn't say how deeply he would cut the rate, but said it could be trimmed in return for reducing corporate tax breaks, simplifying the tax system." (bob davis and amy chozick, "(candidate last) plans spending boost, possible cut in business tax," <i>the wall street journal</i>, 6/17/08) </p><p><b>just last month, (candidate full) called corporate tax cuts "the exact wrong prescription for america." </b>(candidate last): "and his proposals, which are essentially $300 billion worth of corporate tax cuts ... i think is the exact wrong prescription for america." (nbc's "meet the press," 5/4/08) </p><p><b><u><br/>change #5: (candidate full) has changed positions on the d.c. handgun ban</u></b> </p><p><b>in june 2008, (candidate full) said he thought the d.c. handgun ban was unconstitutional. </b>(candidate last): "it looks to me that the d.c. handgun ban overshot the runway. that it went beyond constitutional limits." (bloomberg's "taking stock," 6/26/08) </p><p><b>(candidate last) campaign: "(candidate last) believes the d.c. handgun law is constitutional." </b>"[t]he campaign of (PARTY NAME) presidential hopeful (candidate full) said that he '...believes that we can recognize and respect the rights of law-abiding gun owners and the right of local communities to enact common sense laws to combat violence and save lives. (candidate last) believes the d.c. handgun law is constitutional.'" (james oliphant and michael j. higgins, "court to hear gun case," <i>chicago tribune</i>, 11/20/07) </p><p><b>during an interview, (candidate full) acknowledged his support for the d.c. gun ban. </b>questioner leon harris: "one other issue that's of great importance here in the district as well is gun control. you said in idaho recently - i'm quoting here - 'i have no intention of taking away folks' guns,' but you support the d.c. handgun ban." (candidate last): "right." (leon harris and sen. (candidate full), forum sponsored by abc and politico.com, washington, dc, 2/12/08) </p><p><b><u><br/>change #6: (candidate full) has shifted from opposing welfare reform to celebrating welfare reform in a television ad</u></b></p><p><b>in his newest television ad, (candidate full) touts his role in slashing welfare rolls, but leaves out that he was against the 1996 federal legislation that enacted welfare reform. </b>"(candidate full) aligned himself with welfare reform on monday, launching a television ad which touts the way the overhaul 'slashed the rolls by 80 percent.' (candidate last) leaves out, however, that he was against the 1996 federal legislation which precipitated the caseload reduction." (teddy davis and gregory wallace, "(candidate last) shifts on welfare reform," abc news' "political radar" blog, <a href="http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalradar/2008/07/(candidate last)-shifts-on.html">http://blogs.abcnews.com</a>, posted 7/1/08) </p><p><b>in 1997, (candidate full) said he would have probably not supported federal welfare reform legislation. </b>"'i am not a defender of the status quo with respect to welfare,' (candidate last) said on the floor of the illinois state senate on may 31, 1997. 'having said that, i probably would not have supported the federal legislation, because i think it had some problems.'" (teddy davis and gregory wallace, "(candidate last) shifts on welfare reform," abc news' "political radar" blog, <a href="http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalradar/2008/07/(candidate last)-shifts-on.html">http://blogs.abcnews.com</a>, posted 7/1/08) </p><p><b><u><br/>change #7: as a presidential candidate, (candidate full) criticizes the administration's energy policy despite having voted for the 2005 bush-cheney energy bill</u></b> </p><p><b>(candidate full) attacks (candidate full) on energy policy, saying he will be a "third bush term." (candidate last): </b>"make no mistake, this is an area where (candidate full) is offering a third bush term." (thomas fitzgerald, "(candidate last) knocks (candidate last), says primary fight not hurting, <i>philadelphia inquirer</i>, 4/1/08) </p><p><b>"(candidate last), of course, voted for the 2005 energy bill, which passed the senate overwhelmingly 74-26."</b> (jake tapper, "who's offering a 3rd bush term on energy?" <i>abc news'</i> "political punch" blog, <a href="http://blogs.abcnews.com/politicalpunch/2008/04/whos-offering-a.html">blogs.abcnews.com</a>, 4/3/08) </p><p><b>"someone else who voted against it? the candidate whom (candidate last) says is offering 'a third bush term' on energy policy -- (candidate full)." </b>(jake tapper, "who's offering a 